hands_on_practices.solution:
We have the dispersion relation  
$$k(\omega)=\frac{n(\omega)\,\omega}{c},$$  
and by definition the group velocity  
$$v_g=\frac{d\omega}{dk}=\Bigl(\frac{dk}{d\omega}\Bigr)^{-1}.$$  
1. Compute  
$$\frac{dk}{d\omega}
=\frac{1}{c}\Bigl(n+\omega\frac{dn}{d\omega}\Bigr)$$  
so  
$$v_g=\frac{c}{\,n+\omega\,(dn/d\omega)\,}.$$

2. From the Sellmeier model  
$$n^2=1+\frac{A\,\omega_0^2}{\omega_0^2-\omega^2},$$  
we get  
$$\frac{d(n^2)}{d\omega}
=\frac{2A\,\omega_0^2\,\omega}{(\omega_0^2-\omega^2)^2},$$  
and hence  
$$\frac{dn}{d\omega}
=\frac{1}{2n}\frac{d(n^2)}{d\omega}
=\frac{A\,\omega_0^2\,\omega}{n\,(\omega_0^2-\omega^2)^2}.$$

3. Substitute into the denominator of $v_g$:  
$$n+\omega\frac{dn}{d\omega}
=n+\frac{A\,\omega_0^2\,\omega^2}{n(\omega_0^2-\omega^2)^2}.$$

4. Introduce $\omega=\alpha\omega_0$ so that $\omega_0^2-\omega^2=\omega_0^2(1-\alpha^2)$. Then  
$$n^2=1+\frac{A}{1-\alpha^2}
=\frac{1-\alpha^2+A}{1-\alpha^2},\qquad
\frac{A\,\omega_0^2\,\omega^2}{(\omega_0^2-\omega^2)^2}
=\frac{A\,\alpha^2}{(1-\alpha^2)^2}.$$  
Hence  
$$n+\omega\frac{dn}{d\omega}
=\frac{(1-\alpha^2+A)/(1-\alpha^2)+A\alpha^2/(1-\alpha^2)^2}{\,n}
=\frac{\,(1-\alpha^2)^2 + A\,}{(1-\alpha^2)^2}\,\frac{1}{n}.$$

5. Finally  
$$v_g=\frac{c}{n+\omega\,dn/d\omega}
=c\,n\,\frac{(1-\alpha^2)^2}{(1-\alpha^2)^2+A}
=c\,\frac{(1-\alpha^2)^2\sqrt{\frac{1-\alpha^2+A}{1-\alpha^2}}}
{(1-\alpha^2)^2+A}
=c\,\frac{(1-\alpha^2)^{3/2}\sqrt{1-\alpha^2+A}}{(1-\alpha^2)^2+A}.$$
